dead samurai.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This radically non-linear structure, with its profound implications about the fallibility of perspective, impressed judges at the 1951 Venice Film Festival. They awarded Akira Kurosawa’s film the Golden Lion, helping to encourage a broader interest in Japanese film in the west. With its snaking bolero-like score and poetic use of dappled forest light, Rashomon is a work of enduring ambiguity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>“What is the truth – the perceived, or the real? What is justice? And who decides? A story of a murder told from four different angles by four different people asks troubling questions of us.” <strong>Ranjita Biswas</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>“Probably the greatest testament to what film as an artform can do.” <strong>Johannes Lõhmus</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>“A film that single-handedly changed the way we perceive storytelling, its relationship with the visual medium and the narrative language of cinema itself. This is where the movies’ long love affair with the grammar of time started.” <strong>Rahul Desai</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>“It’s hard to think of a more perfect film about the focal role of storytelling in the construction of human society.” <strong>Vigen Galstyan</strong></p>\r\n","quote":null,"credits":{"director":"Akira Kurosawa","producer":"Jinkichi Minoru, Sojiro Motoki","writer":"Akira Kurosawa, Shinobu Hashimoto","featuring":"Toshiro Mifune, Machiko Kyo, Takashi Shimura"},"year":"1950","nameAndYear":"Rashomon (1950)","links":{"player":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/subscription/film/watch-rashomon-1950-online","southbank":""},"player":{"url":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/subscription/film/watch-rashomon-1950-online","cta":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/subscribe/5647","pillar":"subscription","price":0,"duration":0},"performances":[],"tags":["BFI Player"],"productionCountries":"Japan","runningTime":83,"sightAndSound":{"results":[{"position":41,"tied":true,"category":"critics"},{"position":20,"tied":true,"category":"directors"}],"voters":null}